    "markdown": "---\ntitle: \"Media Sentiment\"\nsubtitle: \"GDELT average-tone of US-presidency English-language news, 2017 to present\"\n---\n\n\n\n::: {.callout-note appearance=\"simple\"}\n**Data source:** [GDELT](https://www.gdeltproject.org/) Doc 2.0 API — daily\naverage *tone* of English-language news articles from US sources matching\n`(\"white house\" OR president OR presidential)`. Licensed **CC-BY-NC**:\nredistributed here for non-commercial analytical purposes with attribution.\nNot affiliated with or endorsed by The GDELT Project.\n\n**Coverage:** For this query, GDELT returned data starting **January 2017**.\nAdministrations before Trump I (Clinton, Bush 43, Obama except his final\nmonth) are absent from this section and show no value.\n:::\n\n## What \"tone\" is, and isn't\n\nGDELT computes tone as the difference between positive- and negative-valence\nword counts in each article, normalized to roughly **−100 to +100**. Typical\nUS political news sits in the **−1 to −3** range — slightly negative on\naverage, which is consistent with news writing conventions (crises and\nconflicts drive more coverage than stability).\n\nTone is not the same as approval:\n\n- It measures the **tone of articles**, not the **opinion of readers**.\n- A very positive article can be written about a policy many readers\n  oppose; a very negative article can cover a president's political\n  opponents.\n- A lexicon-based score cannot distinguish subject from context: \"Trump\n  condemned the attack\" is neutral about Trump but GDELT's tone picks up\n  the word \"attack.\"\n\nTreat this as a **coarse environmental signal** about the media climate\nduring each administration, not a precision instrument.\n\n## Monthly tone — by administration {#timeline}\n\nChart is shaded by administration. Vertical markers are major world events\n(same list used on the [Economic Sentiment](economic.qmd) page). Horizontal\ndotted line is the long-run baseline (-1.45).\n\n\n::: {.cell}\n::: {.cell-output-display}\n\n```{=html}\n<div class=\"echarts4r html-widget html-fill-item\" id=\"htmlwidget-375b2aa956f0b0e9b136\" style=\"width:100%;height:500px;\"></div>\n<script type=\"application/json\" data-for=\"htmlwidget-375b2aa956f0b0e9b136\">{\"x\":{\"theme\":\"custom\",\"tl\":false,\"draw\":true,\"renderer\":\"canvas\",\"events\":[],\"buttons\":[],\"opts\":{\"yAxis\":[{\"show\":true,\"name\":\"Avg tone\"}],\"xAxis\":[{\"data\":[\"2017-01-01\",\"2017-02-01\",\"2017-03-01\",\"2017-04-01\",\"2017-05-01\",\"2017-06-01\",\"2017-07-01\",\"2017-08-01\",\"2017-09-01\",\"2017-10-01\",\"2017-11-01\",\"2017-12-01\",\"2018-01-01\",\"2018-02-01\",\"2018-03-01\",\"2018-04-01\",\"2018-05-01\",\"2018-06-01\",\"2018-07-01\",\"2018-08-01\",\"2018-09-01\",\"2018-10-01\",\"2020-01-01\",\"2020-02-01\",\"2020-03-01\",\"2020-04-01\",\"2020-05-01\",\"2020-06-01\",\"2020-07-01\",\"2020-08-01\",\"2020-09-01\",\"2020-10-01\",\"2021-01-01\",\"2021-02-01\",\"2021-03-01\",\"2021-04-01\",\"2021-05-01\",\"2021-06-01\",\"2021-07-01\",\"2021-08-01\",\"2021-09-01\",\"2021-10-01\",\"2021-11-01\",\"2021-12-01\",\"2022-01-01\",\"2022-02-01\",\"2022-03-01\",\"2022-04-01\",\"2022-05-01\",\"2022-06-01\",\"2022-07-01\",\"2023-01-01\",\"2023-02-01\",\"2023-03-01\",\"2023-04-01\",\"2023-05-01\",\"2023-06-01\",\"2023-07-01\",\"2023-08-01\",\"2023-09-01\",\"2023-10-01\",\"2023-11-01\",\"2023-12-01\",\"2024-01-01\",\"2024-02-01\",\"2024-03-01\",\"2024-04-01\",\"2024-10-01\",\"2024-11-01\",\"2024-12-01\",\"2025-01-01\",\"2025-02-01\",\"2025-03-01\",\"2025-04-01\",\"2025-10-01\",\"2025-11-01\",\"2025-12-01\",\"2026-01-01\",\"2026-02-01\",\"2026-03-01\",\"2026-04-01\"],\"type\":\"time\",\"boundaryGap\":true}],\"legend\":{\"data\":[\"Avg tone (GDELT)\"]},\"series\":[{\"data\":[{\"value\":[\"2017-01-01\",\"-1.166\"]},{\"value\":[\"2017-02-01\",\"-1.364\"]},{\"value\":[\"2017-03-01\",\"-1.373\"]},{\"value\":[\"2017-04-01\",\"-1.562\"]},{\"value\":[\"2017-05-01\",\"-1.259\"]},{\"value\":[\"2017-06-01\",\"-1.296\"